<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-21T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-21T12:00:00-05:00" n="177" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d177">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.51/814.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador to
                                        Germany</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-21T18:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">March 21, 1912—6 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>German minister at Peking instructed to join colleagues of four-power
                                group in protesting against Belgian loan, in which, according to
                                information received by German Foreign Office, both English and
                                French bankers are interested. Germany considers that it would be
                                very unwise to increase size of group, which has already been made
                                somewhat unwieldy by the admission of Japanese syndicate and Russia,
                                whose entry was agreed to for political rather than financial
                                reasons.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Leishman.</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>